Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I asked about this at an API WG meeting but forgot to report back.

Since Glance doesn't use microversions, they said it would be adequate to use any kind of publicly available marker, for example, a release name.  So I guess the thing to do here is say "New in Newton", since this change by itself does not require a minor version bump (at least I'm pretty sure not).

Now that I wrote that, however, this particular situation is actually more complicated.  The disk_format (and container_format) values are site-relative (and there's no code that checks to make sure the values that appear in the schema are a subset of the default values).  Hence, a particular cloud may have supported 'vhdx' since Folsom.  Further, there's no guarantee that an OpenStack cloud will support 'vhdx' in Newton.  An API user needs to make the GET /v2/schemas/image request to see what the valid values are for any particular OpenStack cloud.

Suggestion for handling this inline.

Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

> I asked about this at an API WG meeting but forgot to report back.
 > 
 > Since Glance doesn't use microversions, they said it would be
 > adequate to use any kind of publicly available marker, for example,
 > a release name.  So I guess the thing to do here is say "New in
 > Newton", since this change by itself does not require a minor
 > version bump (at least I'm pretty sure not).
 > 
 > Now that I wrote that, however, this particular situation is
 > actually more complicated.  The disk_format (and container_format)
 > values are site-relative (and there's no code that checks to make
 > sure the values that appear in the schema are a subset of the
 > default values).  Hence, a particular cloud may have supported
 > 'vhdx' since Folsom.  Further, there's no guarantee that an
 > OpenStack cloud will support 'vhdx' in Newton.  An API user needs
 > to make the GET /v2/schemas/image request to see what the valid
 > values are for any particular OpenStack cloud.
 > 
 > Suggestion for handling this inline.

Thanks for the research Brian, very useful.

I think that upstream has never had any vhdx support but that doesn't prevent anyone from supporting it in their cloud as the images will work just fine.


So, I do like your suggestion but if the question is of defaults that come with the source and if that is something needing to go in api-ref then we also need to add the release name against it.

For example in this case,

``vhdx`` is now supported since Newton release.

This is very much like a interoperability with discovery issue where what the sites can expose is part of our schematic response and the upstream documentation needs to indicate what Glance claims to have support for. So, officially we don't support vhdx before Newton.
